<!DOCTYPE theorem	SYSTEM "../Symbols.dtd">
<theorem xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
	xmlns="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/v1/Theorem"    xsi:schemaLocation="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/v1/Theorem    http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/Schemas/v1/Theorem.xsd"
	type="Proposition"
	id="Theo_DotProductAlgebraicProperties">
	<caption>Algebraic Properties of the Dot Product</caption>
	<statement>
      <para>For vectors <latex>\Vect{x},\Vect{y},\Vect{a},\Vect{b}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> and any number <latex>t</latex> in <latex>\RNr</latex>, the following hold:
      	<index.glossary>
      		<term>dot product</term>
      		<term>algebraic properties</term>
      		<info>
      			<para>Click for the proposition formulating the algebraic properties of the dot product operation</para>
      		</info>
      	</index.glossary>
      </para>
		
		<part partid="theopart_Bilinearity">
			<caption>Bilinearity</caption>
			<para>
				<index.glossary>
					<term>bilinearity</term>
					<term>of dot product</term>
					<info>
						<para>The bilinearity property of the dot product asserts that</para>
						<table>
							<row>
								<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{ (\Vect{a} + \Vect{b})}{\Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="center"><para><latex>=</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{\Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y}}\ +\ \DotPr{\Vect{b} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
							</row>
							
							<row>
								<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{(\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}) }</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="center"><para><latex>=</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{x} }\ +\ \DotPr{\Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
							</row>
							<row>
								<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{ (t\cdot \Vect{a}) }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="center"><para><latex>= t\cdot (\DotPr{\Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y} }) =</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ (t \cdot \Vect{y}) }</latex></para></cell>
							</row>
						</table>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
				<index.glossary>
					<term>dot product</term>
					<term>is bilinear</term>
					<info>
						<para>That the dot product is bilinear means</para>
						<table>
							<row>
								<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{(\Vect{a} + \Vect{b})}{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="center"><para><latex>=</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y} }\ +\ \DotPr{\Vect{b} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
							</row>
							<row>
								<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ (\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}) }</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="center"><para><latex>=</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{x} }\ +\ \DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
							</row>
							<row>
								<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{ (t\cdot \Vect{a}) }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="center"><para><latex>= t\cdot (\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y} }) =</latex></para></cell>
								<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ (t \cdot \Vect{y}) }</latex></para></cell>
							</row>
						</table>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
			</para>
			
			<table>
				<row>
					<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{(\Vect{a} + \Vect{b})}{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
					<cell align="center"><para><latex>=</latex></para></cell>
					<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y} }\ +\ \DotPr{ \Vect{b} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ (\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}) }</latex></para></cell>
					<cell align="center"><para><latex>=</latex></para></cell>
					<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{x} }\ +\ \DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{ (t\cdot \Vect{a}) }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></cell>
					<cell align="center"><para><latex>= t\cdot (\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{y} }) =</latex></para></cell>
					<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ (t\cdot \Vect{y}) }</latex></para></cell>
				</row>
			</table>
		</part>
		
		
		<part partid="theopart_Symmetry">
			<caption>Symmetry</caption>
			<para>
				<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{x} } = \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{a} }</latex>
				
				<index.glossary>
					<term>symmetry</term>
					<term>of dot product</term>
					<info>
						<para>The symmetry property of the dot product asserts that</para>
						<math.display>
							<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{x} } = \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{a} }</latex>
						</math.display>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
				
				<index.glossary>
					<term>dot product</term>
					<term>is symmetry</term>
					<info>
						<para>To say that the dot product is symmetry means that</para>
						<math.display>
							<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{x} } = \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{a} }</latex>
						</math.display>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
			</para>
		</part>
		
		
		<part partid="theopart_DotProductPositiveDefinite">
			<caption>Positive definite</caption>
			<para>
				<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} } \geq 0</latex> for all <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
				
				<index.glossary>
					<term>positive definite</term>
					<term>dot product</term>
					<info>
						<para>The positive definiteness property of the dot product asserts that <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} } \geq 0</latex> for all <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>.</para>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
				
				<index.glossary>
					<term>dot product</term>
					<term>positive definite</term>
					<info>
						<para>To say that the dot product is positive definite means that <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} } \geq 0</latex> for all <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>.</para>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
			</para>
		</part>
		
		
		<part partid="theopart_DotProductNonDegenerate">
			<caption>Non-degeneracy</caption>
			<para>
				<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} }</latex> if and only if <latex>\Vect{x} = \Vect{0}</latex>
				
				<index.glossary>
					<term>non-degeneracy</term>
					<term>dot product</term>
					<info>
						<para>The non-degeneracy property of the dot product asserts that </para>
						<para align="center">
							<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} } = 0</latex> if and only if <latex>\Vect{x} = \Vect{0}</latex>
						</para>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
				
				<index.glossary>
					<term>dot product</term>
					<term>non-degenerate</term>
					<info>
						<para>To say that the dot product is non-degenerate means that</para>
						<para align="center">
							<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} } = 0</latex> if and only if <latex>\Vect{x} = \Vect{0}</latex>
						</para>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
			</para>
		</part>
	</statement>
	
	<proof type="Proof">
		<para>Each of these identities follows by computing both sides of the given equation, and checking that the results are equal. So suppose we are given vectors</para>
		
		<computation>
			<left>\Vect{a}</left>
			<center>=</center>
			<right>(a_1,\dots ,a_n)</right>
			<left>\Vect{b}</left>
			<center>=</center>
			<right>(b_1,\dots ,b_n)</right>
			<left>\Vect{x}</left>
			<center>=</center>
			<right>(x_1,\dots ,x_n)</right>
			<left>\Vect{y}</left>
			<center>=</center>
			<right>(y_1,\dots ,y_n)</right>
		</computation>
		
		<para>Then we compute:</para>
		
		<caption>
			<partref>theopart_Bilinearity</partref>
			Bilinearity
		</caption>
		<para>The bilinearity property holds because</para>
		<table align="center">
			<row>
				<cell align="right"><para><latex>\DotPr{ (\Vect{a} + \Vect{b}) }{ \Vect{x} }</latex></para></cell>
				<cell align="center"><para><latex>=</latex></para></cell>
				<cell align="left"><para><latex>\DotPr{ ((a_1,\dots ,a_n) + (b_1,\dots ,b_n)) }{ (x_1,\dots ,x_n) }</latex></para></cell>
			</row>
			
			<row>
				<cell align="right"><para> </para></cell>
				<cell align="center"><para>
					<subordinate><hot><latex>=</latex></hot>
						<info>
							<caption>This computational step holds because</caption>
							<para>... by the definition of vector addition</para>
						</info>
					</subordinate>
				</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left">
					<para><latex>(a_1+b_1,\dots ,a_n+b_n)) \bullet (x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex></para>
				</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell align="right"><para> </para></cell>
				<cell align="center">
					<para>
						<subordinate>
							<hot><latex>=</latex></hot>
							<info>
								<caption>This computational step holds because</caption>
								<para>... by the definition of the dot product</para>
							</info>
						</subordinate>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left"><para><latex>(a_1+b_1)x_1 + \cdots + (a_n+b_n) x_n)</latex></para></cell>
			</row>
			
			<row>
				<cell align="right"><para> </para></cell>
				<cell align="center">
					<para>
						<subordinate><hot><latex>=</latex></hot>
							<info>
								<caption>This computational step holds because</caption>
								<para>... by the distributivity law for real numbers; i.e.</para>
								<para align="center">
									<latex>(a+b)\cdot c = ac + bc</latex>   for arbitrary numbers <latex>a,b,c</latex>
								</para>
							</info>
						</subordinate>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left">
					<para><latex>a_1x_1+b_1x_1 + \cdots + a_nx_n+b_n x_n</latex></para></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell align="right"><para> </para></cell>
				<cell align="center">
					<para>
						<subordinate>
							<hot><latex>=</latex></hot>
							<info>
								<caption>This computational step holds because</caption>
								<para>... by the commutativity law for the addition of real numbers; i.e.</para>
								<para align="center">
									<latex>s + t = t + s</latex>   for arbitrary numbers <latex>s,t</latex>
								</para>
							</info>
						</subordinate>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left">
					<para><latex>a_1x_1+ \cdots + a_nx_n\ +\ b_1x_1 + \cdots + b_n x_n</latex></para>
				</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell align="right">
					<para> </para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="center">
					<para>
						<subordinate>
							<hot>
								<latex>=</latex>
							</hot>
							<info>
								<caption>This computational step holds because</caption>
								<para>... by the definition of the dot product.</para>
							</info>
						</subordinate>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left">
					<para>
						<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{x} } + \DotPr{ \Vect{b} }{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
					</para>
				</cell>
			</row>
		</table>
		<para>as was to be shown. – The remaining bilinearity properties are proved similarly.</para>
		
		
		<caption>
			<partref>theopart_Symmetry</partref>
			Symmetry
		</caption>
		<para>The symmetry property holds because</para>
		<table align="center">
			<row>
				<cell align="right">
					<para>
						<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="center">
					<para>
						<latex>=</latex>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left">
					<para>
						<latex>\DotPr{ (a_1,\dots ,a_n) }{ (x_1,\dots ,x_n) }</latex>
					</para>
				</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell align="right">
					<para> </para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="center">
					<para>
						<subordinate>
							<hot>
								<latex>=</latex>
							</hot>
							<info>
								<caption>This computational step holds because ...</caption>
								<para>... of the definition of the dot product</para>
							</info>
						</subordinate>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left">
					<para>
						<latex>a_1x_1 + \cdots + a_nx_n</latex>
					</para>
				</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell align="right">
					<para> </para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="center">
					<para>
						<subordinate>
							<hot>
								<latex>=</latex>
							</hot>
							<info>
								<caption>This computational step holds because ...</caption>
								<para>... of the commutativity property of multiplication of numbers: <latex>st = ts</latex>
								</para>
							</info>
						</subordinate>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left">
					<para>
						<latex>x_1a_1 + \cdots + x_na_n</latex>
					</para>
				</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell align="right">
					<para> </para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="center">
					<para>
						<subordinate>
							<hot>
								<latex>=</latex>
							</hot>
							<info>
								<caption>This computational step holds because ...</caption>
								<para>... of the definition of the dot product</para>
							</info>
						</subordinate>
					</para>
				</cell>
				<cell align="left">
					<para>
						<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{a} }</latex>
					</para>
				</cell>
			</row>
		</table>
		
		
		<caption>
			<partref>theopart_DotProductPositiveDefinite</partref>
			Positive Definite
		</caption>
		<para>The dot product is positive definite because</para>
		<math.display>
			<latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} } = \DotPr{ (x_1,\dots ,x_n) }{ (x_1,\dots ,x_n) } = x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2} \geq 0</latex>
		</math.display>
		
		
		<caption>
			<partref>theopart_DotProductNonDegenerate</partref>
			Non Degenerate
		</caption>
		<para>The dot product operation is non-degenerate because <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} } = 0</latex> if and only if</para>
		<math.display>
			<latex>x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2} = 0</latex>
		</math.display>
		<para>Now this sum of squares is zero if and only if <latex>x_{i}^{2} = 0</latex> for each <latex>1\leq i\leq n</latex>. Now <latex>x_{i}^{2} = 0</latex> if and only if <latex>x_i=0</latex>, and this is equivalent to</para>
		<para align="center">
			<latex>(x_1,\dots ,x_n) = \Vect{x} = \Vect{0}</latex>.</para>
	</proof>
</theorem>